            <section data-menu=3D"Combine weights and scores" id=3D"combini=
ng-weights-and-scores-to-rank-alternatives">
                <h3>5. Combining weights and scores to rank alternatives</h=
3>
                <p>The final step of AHP is to combine the criterion weight=
s from step 3 with the alternatives=E2=80=99 scores from step 5.</p>
                <h4 id=3D"weighted-sum-model"><strong>Weighted-sum model</s=
trong></h4>
                <p>For each alternative, multiply its score on each criteri=
on by the criterion=E2=80=99s weight and sum the products to get the altern=
ative=E2=80=99s total score, by which the alternatives are ranked.</p>
                <p>The total scores for the three phones in our example are=
 calculated from this simple linear equation:</p>
                <p class=3D"text-center">(W<sub>camera</sub> =C3=97 S<sub>c=
amera</sub>) + (W<sub>storage</sub> =C3=97 S<sub>storage</sub>) + (W<sub>lo=
oks</sub> =C3=97 S<sub>looks</sub>) + (W<sub>price</sub> =C3=97 S<sub>price=
</sub>),</p>
                <p>where the W and S variables are the weights and scores r=
espectively.</p>

                <p>Thus, applying the weights and scores from the tables ab=
ove:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>Phone X: (0.193 =C3=97 0.6) + (0.667 =C3=97 0.07=
7) + (0.081 =C3=97 0.692) + (0.058 =C3=97 0.714) =3D 0.265</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Phone Y: (0.193 =C3=97 0.3) + (0.667 =C3=97 0.30=
8) + (0.081 =C3=97 0.231) + (0.058 =C3=97 0.143) =3D 0.290</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Phone Z: (0.193 =C3=97 0.1) + (0.667 =C3=97 0.61=
5) + (0.081 =C3=97 0.077) + (0.058 =C3=97 0.143) =3D 0.444</p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Now that we=E2=80=99ve gone through the Analytic Hierarc=
hy Process, we find that Phone Z has the highest total score and so is the =
best (first), followed by Phone Y in second place and Phone X in third.</p>
            </section>
        </section>


        <section data-menu=3D"Strengths of AHP" id=3D"strengths-of-ahp">
            <h2>Strengths of AHP</h2>
            <p>AHP is a systematic and logical framework for individuals an=
d organizations to structure decision-making problems and quantify the rela=
tive importance of their criteria and the alternatives they are considering=
 to produce a ranking of the alternatives.</p>
            <p>As decision-makers work to build the hierarchy of an over-ar=
ching decision-making goal, criteria and alternatives, they increase their =
understanding of the decision-making problem, its context and of how they t=
hink and feel about it all.</p>
            <p>Finally, as illustrated by the worked example above, AHP is =
quite straightforward to implement. Albeit the calculations for deriving th=
e criterion weights and alternatives=E2=80=99 scores are intricate, they ca=
n be performed using Excel or specialized software.</p>
        </section>
        <section data-menu=3D"Weaknesses of AHP" id=3D"weaknesses-of-ahp">
            <h2>Weaknesses of AHP</h2>
            <p>Notwithstanding AHP=E2=80=99s widespread use in many sectors=
 worldwide, many weaknesses have been documented by researchers over the ha=
lf century since AHP was invented, including Belton &amp; Gear (1983), Fren=
ch (1986) and Belton &amp; Stewart (2002). Munier &amp; Hontoria=E2=80=99s =
(2021) survey of AHP=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cstructural inability for handling c=
omplex scenarios=E2=80=9D collated criticisms from 101 researchers, grouped=
 under 30 subject headings.</p>
            <p>Many of AHP=E2=80=99s weaknesses are technical in nature and=
 outside the scope of this article (if you are interested, consult the cita=
tions above). The following four weaknesses, which are widely known, are ex=
plained here because, as well as being important, they are easy to understa=
nd.</p>
            <h4 id=3D"meaning-of-ahps-1-9-scale"><strong> Meaning of AHP=E2=
=80=99s 1-9 scale </strong></h4>
            <p>Fundamental to AHP is its pairwise comparison questions and =
their possible 1-9 ratio scale answers and corresponding verbal description=
s of the intensity of decision-makers=E2=80=99 preferences. The scale and v=
alues range from 1 =3D equally important to 9 =3D extremely more important,=
 with intermediate levels, such as 3 =3D moderately more important, 5 =3D s=
trongly more important, 7 =3D very strongly more important, etc.</p>
            <p>Why these levels of intensity and not others? There is no th=
eoretical foundation for equating the values with their verbal descriptions=
.</p>
            <p>And why is AHP=E2=80=99s maximum value 9 =E2=80=93 meaning 9=
-times as important =E2=80=93 instead of another, arbitrary maximum =E2=80=
=93 which could be higher or lower?</p>
            <h4 id=3D"inconsistencies-in-decision-makers-preferences"><stro=
ng> Inconsistencies in decision-makers=E2=80=99 preferences </strong></h4>
            <p>As discussed earlier, the extent of consistency or otherwise=
 =E2=80=93 inconsistency =E2=80=93 in preferences, as captured by entries i=
n a pairwise comparison chart for criteria and alternatives respectively, h=
as two dimensions:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>That <em>matching</em> entries in the chart are reci=
procal: e.g. if you say =E2=80=9Ccamera=E2=80=9D is 4-times as important as=
 =E2=80=9Cprice=E2=80=9D, then =E2=80=9Cprice=E2=80=9D should be <span clas=
s=3D"frac">1/4</span> as important as =E2=80=9Ccamera=E2=80=9D.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>That entries satisfy transitivity: e.g. if =E2=80=9C=
camera=E2=80=9D is 2-times as important as =E2=80=9Cstorage=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cstorage=E2=80=9D is 3-times as important as =E2=80=9Clooks=E2=80=
=9D, then =E2=80=9Ccamera=E2=80=9D should be 6-times as important as =E2=80=
=9Clooks=E2=80=9D.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>Because matching entries in a pairwise comparison chart are =
easy to observe, ensuring they are reciprocals is straightforward.</p>
            <p>On the other hand, ensuring entries satisfy transitivity is =
much harder, if not impossible in practice, especially when you are compari=
ng more than three criteria or alternatives, as the number of pairwise comp=
arisons =E2=80=93 (n<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 n)/2, where n is the number of c=
riteria/alternatives =E2=80=93 increases exponentially.</p>
            <p>Therefore, the goal is to ensure the pairwise comparison cha=
rt is as close to being consistent as possible =E2=80=93 in other words, th=
at it meets some threshold of consistency. As mentioned earlier, =E2=80=9Cc=
onsistency ratios=E2=80=9D can be used to evaluate how close, or far away, =
from being consistent you are, and hence how much confidence you can have i=
n the validity and reliability of your criterion weights and alternatives=
=E2=80=99 scores.</p>
            <p>A related issue that is associated with the previous critici=
sm of AHP=E2=80=99s 1-9 scale is illustrated by this simple example: Suppos=
e =E2=80=9Ccamera=E2=80=9D is 4-times as important as =E2=80=9Cstorage=E2=
=80=9D, and =E2=80=9Cstorage=E2=80=9D is 4-times as important as =E2=80=9Cl=
ooks=E2=80=9D; therefore, =E2=80=9Ccamera=E2=80=9D should be 16-times as im=
portant as =E2=80=9Clooks=E2=80=9D. But the highest point on the ratio scal=
e is 9, i.e. 9-times. Furthermore, in the extreme, if the first two links i=
n this transitivity chain were 9-times as important, then the third link sh=
ould be 81-times!</p>
            <p>AHP does not permit such ratio scale values. AHP=E2=80=99s m=
aximum value is 9 =E2=80=93 hence, virtually, guaranteeing that pairwise co=
mparison charts have inconsistencies.</p>
            <h4 id=3D"rank-reversals"><strong>Rank reversals</strong></h4>
            <p>=E2=80=9CRank reversal=E2=80=9D is the phenomenon whereby wh=
en a new alternative is introduced to an AHP application, despite this new =
alternative not affecting any of the original alternatives included in the =
application, it leads to a change in the original alternatives=E2=80=99 ran=
king: a rank reversal! (Belton &amp; Gear 1983). Rank reversal is sometimes=
 referred to as a violation of an important axiom of rational decision-maki=
ng known as =E2=80=9Cthe independence of irrelevant alternatives=E2=80=9D.<=
/p>
            <p>Thus, imagine if a fourth phone were added to the smartphone=
 example above and this changed how the original three phones, X, Y and Z, =
are ranked relative to each other =E2=80=93 e.g. suppose Phone Z went from =
being first to third? Such a rank reversal would undermine most people=E2=
=80=99s confidence in their results.</p>
            <h4 id=3D"cognitive-difficulty-of-ratio-scale-measurements"><st=
rong> Cognitive difficulty of ratio-scale measurements </strong></h4>
            <p>Most people find answering AHP=E2=80=99s pairwise comparison=
 questions cognitively difficult. Thinking about how strongly you feel abou=
t one criterion, or alternative, relative to another and expressing that in=
tensity on a 0-9 scale, even with verbal equivalents, is an unnatural decis=
ion-making activity that most people have little experience of in their liv=
es.</p>
            <p>In contrast, a more natural decision-making activity is to m=
ake choices between alternatives, in the process revealing your preferences=
. Choosing between alternatives is something we all do dozens if not hundre=
ds of times every day: e.g. =E2=80=9Cwould you like coffee or tea?=E2=80=9D=
, =E2=80=9Cwould you prefer an Android or iOS phone?=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Csha=
ll we go to a movie or to see a band?=E2=80=9D, etc.</p>
        </section>
        <section data-menu=3D"PAPRIKA vs AHP" id=3D"paprika-as-an-alternati=
ve-to-ahp">
            <h2>PAPRIKA as an alternative to AHP</h2>
            <p>A more natural, choice-based process for making decisions th=
at was designed to be as cognitively simple and user-friendly as possible, =
as well as scientifically valid and reliable, is the <a href=3D"https://www=
.1000minds.com/paprika">PAPRIKA method</a> =E2=80=93 an acronym for <em><st=
rong>P</strong>otentially <strong>A</strong>ll <strong>P</strong>airwise <s=
trong>R</strong>an<strong>K</strong>ings of all possible <strong>A</strong>=
lternatives </em> (PAPRIKA) (Hansen &amp; Ombler 2008).</p>
            <p>Instead of asking you to rate how much more important one cr=
iterion or alternative is than another on a 1-9 scale, PAPRIKA simply asks =
you to choose between two hypothetical alternatives defined on only two cri=
teria at time and involving a trade-off.</p>
