v class=3D"dilemma" data-degree=3D"2"><div class=3D"dilemma-side"><div clas=
s=3D"dilemma-side-inner"><div class=3D"dilemma-categorization"><div class=
=3D"dilemma-criterion">Waterproof rating</div><div class=3D"dilemma-level">=
IP68 (up to 1.5m)</div></div><div class=3D"dilemma-categorization"><div cla=
ss=3D"dilemma-criterion">Camera quality</div><div class=3D"dilemma-level">G=
ood =E2=80=93 clear images and decent features</div></div></div><div class=
=3D"dilemma-button dilemma-side-button">This one</div></div><div class=3D"d=
ilemma-side"><div class=3D"dilemma-side-inner"><div class=3D"dilemma-catego=
rization"><div class=3D"dilemma-criterion">Waterproof rating</div><div clas=
s=3D"dilemma-level">IP67 (up to 1m)</div></div><div class=3D"dilemma-catego=
rization"><div class=3D"dilemma-criterion">Camera quality</div><div class=
=3D"dilemma-level">Excellent =E2=80=93 high resolution and professional fea=
tures</div></div></div><div class=3D"dilemma-button dilemma-side-button">Th=
is one</div></div><div class=3D"dilemma-button dilemma-equal-button">They a=
re equal</div></div></div></figure>

            <p>Thus, like AHP, PAPRIKA is based on questions involving pair=
wise comparisons, but much simpler ones involving <em>ordinal</em> instead =
of <em>ratio-scale</em> measurements of your preferences. Therefore, you ca=
n have more confidence in your answers.</p>
            <p>Such simple questions are repeated with different pairs of h=
ypothetical alternatives, always involving trade-offs between different com=
binations of your criteria, two at a time.</p>
            <p>As you answer each question, PAPRIKA adapts by fully exploit=
ing the mathematical and logical properties of weighted-sum models, includi=
ng transitivity (discussed earlier), to select your next question so that y=
ou are asked the minimum number required and your answers are always consis=
tent. From your answers, mathematical methods based on linear programming d=
etermine your criterion weights, which are used to rank any alternatives yo=
u are considering.</p>
            <p>Thus, <a href=3D"https://www.1000minds.com/paprika">PAPRIKA<=
/a>, implemented by 1000minds, is also based on pairwise comparisons but wi=
thout AHP=E2=80=99s weaknesses.</p>
        </section>
        <section data-menu=3D"Conclusion" id=3D"conclusion">
            <h2>Conclusion</h2>
            <p>The Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP) is a systematic framewo=
rk for structuring decision-making problems and using pairwise comparisons =
to quantify the relative importance of the criteria and alternatives to pro=
duce a ranking of alternatives. However, AHP=E2=80=99s weaknesses highlight=
 the usefulness of more natural, choice-based decision-making processes als=
o based on pairwise comparisons like 1000minds=E2=80=99 PAPRIKA method, whi=
ch is available as an alternative approach.</p>
